  "summary": "# Weekly Market Briefing \u2014 Week Ending March 22, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 1. Market Overview\n\nBroad equity markets sold off meaningfully this week. **SPY fell 2.79%** to $648.57 and **QQQ dropped 3.05%** to $582.06, indicating large-cap tech underperformed the broader market. Small caps fared slightly better, with **IWM down 2.52%**, while **DIA declined 2.85%**. This was a broad-based risk-off week with no major index spared \u2014 VTI and VOO mirrored SPY's losses. Elevated volumes across all broad ETFs (SPY at 100M+, IWM at 53M+) confirm this was conviction selling, not a low-liquidity drift.\n\n## 2. Sector Performance\n\n**Energy (XLE +2.44%)** was the clear standout \u2014 the only sector in the green \u2014 likely supported by firming crude prices or geopolitical supply concerns. **Financials (XLF -0.45%)** held up relatively well, possibly benefiting from steeper yield curve expectations.\n\nThe worst performers were **Utilities (XLU -5.52%)**, **Materials (XLB -4.90%)**, **Real Estate (XLRE -4.67%)**, **Consumer Staples (XLP -4.34%)**, and **Consumer Discretionary (XLY -3.98%)**. The sharp sell-off in traditionally defensive sectors (Utilities, Staples, REITs) alongside rate-sensitive areas suggests rising interest rate fears or a sudden unwinding of crowded defensive positioning. **Healthcare (XLV -3.76%)** also lagged, dragged by individual names (see below).\n\n## 3. Notable Movers\n\n- **ABBV (-7.40%)** was the week's biggest individual decliner among watched names \u2014 potentially pipeline or regulatory news. Volume at 10.3M warrants attention.\n- **TSLA (-6.98%)** continued its volatile pattern on extremely high volume (59.5M), with its P/E of 343.9 leaving no margin for disappointment.\n- **SHOP (-7.74%)** saw the steepest drop among growth names on modest volume.\n- **NVDA (-5.74%)** sold off hard on massive volume (187M shares), the highest on the watchlist by far.\n- **AMD (+2.42%)** was a rare bright spot in tech, possibly benefiting from competitive positioning or rotation within semis.\n- **T (+2.09%)**, **CVX (+2.48%)**, and **XOM (+1.55%)** bucked the selloff \u2014 energy and value/income names attracted flows.\n\n## 4. Key Metrics\n\n- **Precious metals collapsed**: GLD (-10.22%) and SLV (-15.98%) saw extraordinary drawdowns. This is unusual during equity weakness and may indicate margin/liquidity-driven forced selling or a sharp dollar rally.\n- **Bonds offered little shelter**: BND (-0.89%) and TLT (-1.58%) declined, confirming this was not a classic flight-to-quality week. Stocks, bonds, and metals all fell together \u2014 a rare and concerning correlation pattern.\n- **Stretched valuations persist**: PLTR (239x), TSLA (344x), and SHOP (126x) remain vulnerable in a rising-rate environment. AVGO at 60.6x also stands out relative to semiconductor peers.\n\n## 5. Themes to Watch\n\n- **Correlated drawdowns** across equities, bonds, and gold echo liquidity stress episodes \u2014 monitor credit spreads and dollar strength closely.\n- **Energy's divergence** \u2014 is this the start of a sustained rotation or a one-week anomaly?\n- **NVDA's volume spike** \u2014 watch for follow-through; any break in AI-trade leadership could cascade through tech.\n- **Rate sensitivity** \u2014 the damage to Utilities, REITs, and long-duration bonds suggests markets may be repricing Fed expectations ahead of next week's data.\n- **Crypto weakness** (BTC -3.6%, ETH -5.7%, ADA -6.6%) is consistent with broad risk-off sentiment.\n\n---\n\n*This briefing is for informational purposes only. No specific trade recommendations are included.*",
